NGS analysis report

Author: Aleksandra Gomółka

Introduction

The analysis is based on the work by Rühl C and colleagues who performed the research on alternative splicing patterns in plants with increased and decreased levels of the 3 Arabidopsis Polypyrimidine-tract binding protein homologues in comparison to wild type samples, determined in duplicates.

The database includes, among others, two replicas of readings WT (wild type) and two replicas of readings: OE1, OE2, OE3 (over expressed). Further analysis focused on only OE1 and compared it to the wild type.

Source: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/geo/query/acc.cgi?acc=GSE41433

Alignment

Subread analysis

The “subread” package available in R was used to carry out the alignment. Subread is a software tool package for the alignment of both DNA-seq and RNA-seq read data, quantification, and mutation detection. The Subread package consists of five separate tools:

  • Subread, a read aligner for both RNA-seq and DNA-seq data,
  • Subjunc, read aligner for RNA-seq data, detection of exon-exon junctions and gene fusion events,
  • FeatureCounts, read counting,
  • Sublong, for aligning long reads using the seed-and-vote technique
  • ExactSNP, a single-nucleotide polymorphism discovery.

Operation: Sequence alignment
Input: FASTA files
Output: BAM files

Alignment is performed to align the analyzed sequences (input reads) against the reference sequence (genom) to determine where they are mapped and to finally quantify gene-level expression and discover differentially expressed genes.Aligner Subread carries out local alignments for RNA-seq reads in two steps.

Step 1: Building an index

The subread-buildindex (buildindex function in Rsubread) program builds an index for reference genome by creating a hash table in which keys are 16bp mers (subreads) extracted from the genome and values are their chromosomal locations.

library(Rsubread)

#building index for RSubread (where TAIR9 is the genom)
buildindex(
  basename="TAIR9g",
  reference="data/TAIR9.fa")

Step 2: Aligning the reads (read mapping using Subjunc)

Subjunc not only performs read alignments but also detects exon-exon junctions. It is also used for others purposes of the RNA-seq data analysis such as alternative splicing analysis and genomic mutation detection. There are two files produced after mapping: one is a BAM-format file including mapping results and the other possible format is a BED-format file including discovered exon-exon junctions.

#mapping WT_R1
subjunc("TAIR9g", "data/WT_R1.fastq", output_file = "WT_R1.bam",
        nthreads = 4, reportAllJunctions = TRUE)

Count reads by genomic features

The next step is to assign mapped sequencing reads to specified genomic features.

fc <- featureCounts(c("WT_R1.bam","WT_R2.bam", "OE1_R1.bam", "OE1_R2.bam"), 
                    annot.ext = "data/TAIR9.gtf", 
                    isGTFAnnotationFile = TRUE,
                    juncCounts = TRUE,
                    nthreads = 4)

FeatureCounts is a general-purpose read summarization function that can assign mapped reads from genomic RNA sequencing to genomic features. The function takes as input a set of BAM files containing read mapping results, which was generated by subjunc. GTF was selected as the annotation format to specify the genomic. features. As a result of the function, information about the following components was obtained:

  • counts - a data matrix containing read counts for each feature for each library
  • counts_junction (optional) - a data frame including primary and secondary genes overlapping an exon junction
  • annotation - a data frame with the annotation information for the features, like: GeneID, Chr (chromosome), Start, End and Length.
  • targets - list of input files
  • stat - statistics, a data frame giving number of successfully assigned reads (reads which have been mapped to the genome in region when features are: exons, genes) in each library and also number of unassigned reads falling in each filtering category (e.g. unassigned and unmapped reads which are not mapped anywhere, this may be due to contamination, fragments, remnants of the protocol or even incomplete genome sequence or unassigned and no features reads which may come from impurities or new genes/exons that have not yet been discovered)
head(fc$counts)

Particular attention was paid to the “counts” parameters. The columns contain the sample names and the rows contain the names of the genes. Note that the sequencing depth for OE1_R1 is significantly lower than the others. In order to make better comparisons, this number should be multiplied. The variance of the results is quite large. Determining the differences in the counts, as well as their significance, is the purpose of this statistical analysis.

Therefore, the next step will be to perform a differential expression analysis.

Differential expression analysis (DEA)

Limma

Limma for genes

In the limma approach to RNA-seq, read counts are converted to log2-counts-per-million (logCPM) and the mean-variance relationship is modeled either with precision weights or with an empirical Bayes prior trend. We distinguish two approaches: voom and limma-trend (the prior trend approach). The analysis used the precision weights approach called “voom”.

Step 1: Making a count matrix

RNA-seq data usually arrives in the form of FastQ or BAM files of unaligned reads. The reads need to be mapped to a reference genome or transcriptome, then summarized at the exon or gene level to produce a matrix of counts. Generally, it is created a matrix of read counts, with rows for genes and columns for samples.

library(limma)

#count matrix
#changing the name of the columns and their order
genes.merged <- fc$counts[, c(3, 4, 1, 2)]
colnames(genes.merged) <- c("OE_1_R1", "OE_1_R2", "WT_R1", "WT_R2")

#extracting group info
#extraction of only the first two characters of the name and grouping into appropriate classes
samples <- substr(colnames(genes.merged), 0, 2)

#creating design data frame
design <- data.frame(OEs=ifelse(samples=="OE", 1,0),
                     WTs=ifelse(samples=="WT", 1, 0))
rownames(design) <- colnames(genes.merged)
design
##         OEs WTs
## OE_1_R1   1   0
## OE_1_R2   1   0
## WT_R1     0   1
## WT_R2     0   1
#creating contrast(s) matrix
#contrasts it is useful with more groups
cm <- makeContrasts(OEvsWT=OEs-WTs,
                    levels=design)
cm
##       Contrasts
## Levels OEvsWT
##    OEs      1
##    WTs     -1

Step 2: Normalization and filtering

In this approach, the voom transformation is applied to the normalized and filtered DGEList object. DGEList object is created from a table of counts (rows=features, columns=samples), group indicator for each column, library size (optional) and a table of feature annotation (optional).

dge <- DGEList(counts = genes.merged)
dge$samples

In this case, we can observe summary statistics e.g. how many reads we have for every sample.

#TMM normalization - normalization between groups with taking into account that most genes do not change their expression

Step 3: Differential expression: voom

The next step is to perform variance estimation within groups and between groups. It is important in the next steps to be able to determine for each gene separately whether the differences between the groups are greater than the variance of all groups.

#linear model fit with limma
#to refine the results we can use robust method to perform the fit with maximal number of iterations (9999) excluding outliers
f.t <- lmFit(v, design)

#contrasts fit
cf <- contrasts.fit(f.t, cm)

#Bayes correction - counteracts too many false positive results
fe <- eBayes(cf, proportion = 0.01)

When we analyze many features at the same time (and doing for them some statistical analysis), we must perform multiple testing correction to counteract a false positive results. In simple terms, the statistical significance level (p-value) should be reduced. To decrease the false discovery rate we use the Benjamini-Hochberg procedure. We assume that the features we are testing (genes in our case) are independent. Which is not entirely true, because there are many molecular mechanisms that affect gene regulation. Therefore, in future analyzes should try to use other methods (e.g BY) and compare the results.

#multiple testing correction approach
adj.method = "BH"
#top table showing treshold, p-value and applying multiple testing correction
limma.countsTMMvoom.genes <- topTable(fe, number=Inf, adjust.method=adj.method, sort.by='none')
head(limma.countsTMMvoom.genes)
##                logFC  AveExpr          t   P.Value adj.P.Val         B
## AT1G01010 -0.5384658 3.516210 -1.8126731 0.1165419 0.9999705 -4.485710
## AT1G01020  0.1130875 4.260716  0.4270953 0.6832468 0.9999705 -4.674720
## AT1G01030  0.3527949 2.617181  0.9635067 0.3701242 0.9999705 -4.601583
## AT1G01040  0.2664728 5.663624  0.9197004 0.3909330 0.9999705 -4.619157
## AT1G01050 -0.1000209 6.175049 -0.3954002 0.7053372 0.9999705 -4.686334
## AT1G01060  0.4224567 7.003161  0.6968894 0.5102757 0.9999705 -4.647452

We get statistics for each gene (gene names in rows), for example: local change (differences between groups (overexpressed vs wild type) on a log scale), avarage expression, T-statistic, p-value and addjusted p-value (after multiple testing correction). We usually set the p-value to 0.05. So we can determine for which genes or for how many genes the p-value is less than 5%.

sum(limma.countsTMMvoom.genes$adj.P.Val<0.05)
## [1] 1
which(limma.countsTMMvoom.genes$adj.P.Val<0.05)
## [1] 10029
limma.countsTMMvoom.genes[which(limma.countsTMMvoom.genes$adj.P.Val<0.05),]
##            logFC AveExpr       t      P.Value  adj.P.Val         B
## AT3G01150 5.9992  7.9388 16.2625 1.831252e-06 0.04377607 -4.147026

Following the above steps, we can conclude that the only gene that shows a statistically significant change in expression is AT3G01150. From a statistical point of view, a p-value less than 0.05 means that the null hypothesis of no differences between the test type and the wild type should be rejected and the alternative hypothesis accepted.

However, the p-value for this gene is less than 5%, but not that much. This is due to the number of technical replicates, because the statistical analysis significantly depends on them. In our case we have only two technical replicates. For a more accurate analysis it would be better to use more technical replicates.

A similar analysis using a different multiple-testing correction, which takes into account the relationships between genes is shown below.

adj.method = "BY"

limma.countsTMMvoom.genes <- topTable(fe, number=Inf, adjust.method=adj.method, sort.by='none')

sum(limma.countsTMMvoom.genes$adj.P.Val<0.05)
## [1] 0
which(limma.countsTMMvoom.genes$adj.P.Val<0.05)
## integer(0)
limma.countsTMMvoom.genes[which(limma.countsTMMvoom.genes$adj.P.Val<0.05),]
## [1] logFC     AveExpr   t         P.Value   adj.P.Val B        
## <0 rows> (or 0-length row.names)

We get zero statistically significant results. Therefore, we can conclude that in the case of using only two technical replicates, this method is too rigorous.

The aim of the analysis was to investigate which genes differed significantly in the group.

We observe that the only one point (magenta point) is statistically significant. The vast majority of points (black points) are not statistically significant.

Transcript number 4 appears to be responsible for the level of expression of the gene, while the others have little influence.

Actually, the mRNA transcript is sequenced and the expression of the gene is the sum of expression of all the transcripts of this gene. Consequently, there are no points above the diagonal, because it is not possible for the transcript expression level to be greater than the gene expression level (considering the log10 scale in the graph). Diagonal (the orange line) thus represents a situation where transcript expression is equal to gen expression (there is only one transcript per gene or there are many transcripts but only the one takes up the whole expression).

EdgeR

Then, analysis was performed using another tool - EdgeR.

EdgeR offers many variants on analyses. The glm (linear model) approach is more popular than the classic approach as it offers great flexibilities. There are two testing methods:

  • likelihood ratio tests
  • quasi-likelihood F-tests

The quasi-likelihood method is highly recommended for differential expression analyses of bulk RNA-seq data as it gives stricter error rate control by accounting for the uncertainty in dispersion estimation. The likelihood ratio test can be useful in some special cases such as single cell RNA-seq and datasets with no replicates.

In the analysis of RNA-seq, the quasi-likelihood F-test approach is most often used, but in our case we have only two technical replicates and four samples, which may affect the results. Therefore, both methods were used and the obtained results were compared.

EdgeR for genes

library(edgeR)

group <- factor(c(2,2,1,1)) #overexpression type (group nr 2), wild type (group nr 1)
y <- DGEList(counts=genes.merged, group=group) #merge object to a table of counts

keep <- filterByExpr(y)
y <- y[keep,,keep.lib.sizes=FALSE]
y <- calcNormFactors(y) #calculating of normalization factors (TMM)
design <- model.matrix(~group) #creating design data frame - determination of groups for each sample
y <- estimateDisp(y, design) #calculation of variance within all groups and between groups
  • To perform quasi-likelihood F-tests:
fit <- glmQLFit(y,design) #linear model
qlf <- glmQLFTest(fit,coef=2) #F-test application
topTags(qlf)

We observe that the previously selected gene (AT3G01150) shows the highest expression among the genes available in the data set. The logFC parameter is similar to the previously obtained value. Average expression is expressed as logCPM (counts per million). However, we can see that the adjusted FDR (BH multiple testing approach) is not statistically significant. This is because this approach is too strict with only two replicas. So we can expect more false positive results than there really should be.

Again, the most significant is AT3G01150_ID4, but we have also eight transcripts with significant difference.

We observe that in the quasi-likelihood approach, the transcript shows a change close to the determined statistical significance (0.05), but the gene is very far from this. The signal comes mainly from this one transcript. At the gene level, we get expression from other transcripts, which makes it difficult to get to a significant level. For a less restrictive method we get more genes/transcripts with significant level. In sum, at the transcript level, it’s much easier to get a significant level because we don’t observe masking by the others. We can also consider the summation effect from transcripts that do not show a significant level when taken separately, but at the gene level they do.

DESeq2

The package DESeq2 provides methods to test for differential expression by use of negative binomial generalized linear models; the estimates of dispersion and logarithmic fold changes incorporate data-driven prior distributions.

In this example, the “DESeqDataSetFromMatrix” function creates a DESeqDataSet object from the count data and design matrix. The “DESeq” function performs the differential expression analysis, and the results are obtained using the “results” function. Finally, the differentially expressed genes are identified based on an adjusted p-value threshold of 0.05.

DESeq2 for genes

Step 1: Preparing data

library(DESeq2)

#create a matrix with sample info (with sample names in rows)
colData <- data.frame(colnames(genes.merged), condition = factor(c(1, 1, 0, 0)))
rownames(colData) <- colnames(genes.merged)
#making sure the row names in colData matches to column names in countData (genes.merged)
all(colnames(genes.merged) %in% rownames(colData))
## [1] TRUE
#checking are they in the same order
all(colnames(genes.merged) == rownames(colData))
## [1] TRUE

Step 2: Construct a DESeqDataSet object

#create a DESeqDataSet
#the "round" function is used because the variable countData takes a matrix of non-negative integers
#the "design" variable groups samples into overexpressed (1) and wild type (0)

dds <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(countData=round(genes.merged), colData=colData, 
                             design = ~ condition)
## converting counts to integer mode

The next step may be to filter the data through removing rows with low gene counts. It is recommended to keep rows that have at least 10 reads total. This step is recommended but not required, therefore this step is omitted from this analysis (in particular to compare the results with previous analyzes that did not include this step).

#set the factor level - to determine the reference group
dds$condition <- relevel(dds$condition, ref = "0")

Step 3: Run DESeq analysis

#run the DESeq
dds <- DESeq(dds)
## estimating size factors
## estimating dispersions
## gene-wise dispersion estimates
## mean-dispersion relationship
## final dispersion estimates
## fitting model and testing
#get the results
res <- results(dds)

Log-fold change parameter is calculating for “condition” factor between over expressed (1) and wild type (0). All of values for logFC are only for over expressed because they are compared to the wild type. Positive values of the logFC parameter determine the up regulation. On the other hand, negative values of the logFC parameter determine the down regulation.The statistical test used is the Wald test. The resulting dataframe has multiple columns: baseMean (same as Average expression), log2FoldChange (fold-change for gene in over expressed condition with compared to the wild type), lfcSE (standard error estimates for logFC), stat (Wald test values for these genes), pvalue (p-value of the test statistic for this genes), padj (corrected p-values for multiple testing).

Overall, we can conclude that we have obtained similar statistics and information from previous analyses, but with different assays (variable names).

plotMA(res)

A graph of log-fold change vs. mean of normalized counts was obtained. This plot shows as the genes which are differentially expressed. In this plot we can see genes in the upper right or the lower right quadrant of this plot, which means that this genes would have high mean of normalized counts and high log-fold change which would make them very interesting candidates to be further looked into.

gen.sel <- "AT3G01150"
trans.sel <- mapping[mapping[,"genes"] == gen.sel, "transcripts"]

pchs <- rep("+", dim(res)[1])
cols <- rep("black", dim(res)[1])
names(pchs) <- names(cols) <- rownames(res)

res <- res[complete.cases(res$padj), ] #it is necessary to remove the 'NA' values
sig <- res$padj < 0.05
sel_row <- rownames(res) == trans.sel


#determining the shape of the points to distinguish the significant from the non-significant
pchs[sig] <- "X"
pchs[!sig] <- "+"

#specifying the color of points to distinguish significant from non-significant, as well as to distinguish gen.sel
cols[sig & !sel_row] <- "blue"
cols[sel_row] <- "red"

plot(log10(res$baseMean+0.1), res$log2FoldChange,
     xlab = "BaseMean", ylab="logFC", main = "MA plot", pch=pchs, col=cols)
abline(h=0, col="orange", lwd=2)

The chart includes all transcripts showing statistically significant results (padj-value less than 0.05). The graph takes into account the logarithmic transformation for the baseMean, due to the wide range of values of this variable. The distribution of the data changed slightly (less noise) after removing the rows with NA values (especially those rows with NA values for padj). But in general, the most important information about the unique over expression of one of the transcripts has been captured. Therefore, we can say that the cumulative chart confirms the performed statistical analysis.

Summary

To summarize, the analysis provided information about the unique up regulation of the gene AT3G01150 and the corresponding ID4 transcript. Each of the methods used to study differential expression showed distinct characteristics and results, but all of them singled out this particular gene and transcript as the most important in the analysis. Each of the tests was characterized by a different accuracy and severity in evaluating the data. The differences in the results of differential expression methods such as limma, edgeR, and DESeq can come from various sources:

  • Statistical model: The statistical models used by each method to calculate the significance of differential gene/transcript expression are different, leading to different results.

  • Data normalization: Different normalization methods can affect the results, particularly when the data has high levels of variability or technical noise.

  • Batch effects correction: The methods used to correct for batch effects, a systematic bias that can occur when samples are processed in different batches, can also affect the results.

  • Outlier handling: The methods used to handle outliers, which can be caused by technical issues or biological variability, can also influence the results.

  • Fold change calculation: The methods used to calculate fold changes, which are used to quantify the magnitude of differential gene/transcript expression, can also vary between methods and impact the results.

In conclusion, the choice of differential gene/transcript expression method should be based on the specifics of the experiment, the quality of the data, and the biological question being asked.
